1. Distributed web infrastructure

User types www.foobar.com in the browser.
DNS sends the request to the load balancer IP.
The load balancer, HAProxy, sends the request to one of the two servers.

Infrastructure:

User
  |
DNS: www.foobar.com
  |
HAProxy load balancer
  |
  |----------|
  v          v
Server 1    Server 2
Nginx       Nginx
App server  App server
Codebase    Codebase
MySQL       MySQL

Why we added HAProxy:
HAProxy is added to share traffic between the two servers.
It helps the website handle more users.

Why we added a second server:
The second server helps reduce pressure on one server.
If one server has a problem, the other server can still work.

Load balancer algorithm:
The load balancer uses Round Robin.
This means requests are sent one by one to each server.
Example:
Request 1 goes to Server 1.
Request 2 goes to Server 2.
Request 3 goes back to Server 1.

Active-Active setup:
This is Active-Active because both servers are working at the same time.

Active-Active means all servers receive traffic.
Active-Passive means one server works and the other waits as backup.

Database Primary-Replica:
One MySQL database is Primary.
The other MySQL database is Replica.

The Primary database receives write operations like insert, update, and delete.
The Replica database copies data from the Primary database.
The Replica is mainly used for read operations.

Difference between Primary and Replica:
The application writes data to the Primary database.
The application can read data from the Replica database.
The Primary is the main database.
The Replica is a copy used to reduce load.

Issues:

1. SPOF:
The load balancer is a single point of failure.
If HAProxy goes down, the website is down.
The Primary database is also a single point of failure for write operations.

2. Security:
There is no firewall.
There is no HTTPS.
Traffic is not protected.

3. No monitoring:
There is no monitoring system.
We cannot easily know if a server is down or overloaded.
